<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<HEAD>A FARMER just return'd from Meet|ing on THANKSGIVING DAY.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="prologue">
<HEAD>PROLOGUE.</HEAD>
<L>[TO night the Muse attempts to show</L>
<L>The Miser and the aukward Beau;</L>
<L>Where <HI>Dan.</HI> and <HI>Joth.</HI> together join,</L>
<L>On sumptuous dish with Father dine.</L>
<L>While Mother she the table sets,</L>
<L>Both <HI>Sal.</HI> and <HI>Mat.</HI> assist her next;</L>
<L><PB N="5" REF="015290_0005_0F98CF2E0599DE50">Next <HI>Lyon</HI> he puts in his clame,</L>
<L>And Mother thinks him much to blame&punc;</L>
<L>She in a passion gives a kick,</L>
<L>Father he being fond of <HI>Jack,</HI></L>
<L>Permitted the poor puppy in,</L>
<L>To lap the gravy spilt&mdash;quite clean.</L>
<L>Master and <HI>Jack</HI> always agreed,</L>
<L>He taught him well to say his creed,</L>
<L>And all the words that e'er they had,</L>
<L>Was Paper Money's being bad.</L>
<L>Master insists and makes it so,</L>
<L>That Paper Money wou'd not do&punc;</L>
<L><HI>Jack</HI> he insists, and says no more,</L>
<L>But such examples hurts the Poor.]</L>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="body of play">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>JACK,</HI> take care of the horses, give 'em some of that best rowen,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JACK.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yesse, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JONATHAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, how does Father do&mdash; and all your folks?&mdash;'Tis quite cold.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why thank ye child&punc; how do you do?&mdash;<HI>Mat.</HI> Draw a mug of cyder, put a good stout pepper-pad in't, heat it well&mdash; I feel quite chilly myself. Why I have got good cyder enough; and this year intend to take care of't. Why <HI>Jonathan</HI> I have been offered five dollars a barrel, and wouldn't look at it, it will fetch me fifteen in the spring.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JONATHAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Father, that it will, and that won't be near so dear as rum is now in town: I am glad we can say this of the town folks, that we a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">e even with them now, only that we should have six Continental dollars
<PB N="6" REF="015290_0006_0F98CF2EC5A88838">
for a load of wood; I'll sell no more for five, I know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never fear, never fear, <HI>Jonathan,</HI> the times are now in our hands, and if we don't improve this opportunity I don't see which way in the world we could ever an|swer to ourselves with a good conscience.&mdash; Hem. Daughter <HI>Sarah</HI> my service t'ye.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SARAH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank'e, pray Father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JOTHAM.</SPEAKER>
<P>Father your health; Mother yours; herest'e all.
<STAGE>[Drinks.]</STAGE>
This is right down good cyder as ever man needs drink.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SARAH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, <HI>Jotham,</HI> 'tis, and Mo|ther's pudding looks charming too.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come Father, dinner's ready.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WIFE.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, You, do sit down, all sit down, sit down, the pudding will get cold, and then 'twill be good for nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, come let's crave a bles<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">sing.
<STAGE>[The Farmer proceeds to crave a blessing&punc; in the run of which he pities the poor and needy thro'out the world.]</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WIFE.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come cut for yourselves, I am quite ashamed of my pudding; I think it is the poorest that ever I made; however I don't care, as the times is I believe the town folks wou'd jump at a bit on't poor as it is.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SARAH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why 'tis said that scornful dogs sometimes jump&punc; at a dirty pudding.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WIFE.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why <HI>Sarah!</HI> I'm sure my pud|ding isn't dirty, I never was reckoned a slut in all my life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="7" REF="015290_0007_0F98CF30470B2190">
<SPEAKER>SARAH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Mother! I don't mean <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">o, on|ly that the town folks us'd to scorn every thing but the best, but now they'd be glad even of a crust of your pudding. I expect some of them along to-morrow or next day beg|ging as the Indians us'd to do the day after thanksgiving. I can't but laugh to see how foolish they'l look.&mdash;He! he! he!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WIFE.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! ha! It would be a pret|ty sight too, <HI>Sarah.</HI> Ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! ha! Well, I can't but laugh too. Ha! ha! ha! Draw another mug of cyder; take two cups with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JACK.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well Masser, I don't tink 'tis fair ting when poor fok he canno get no noting in he belly; Masser every ting, I do <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">o no what Masser mean; he pray, he pray, he <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> Lord he pity poor ebery where; he no g<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">v<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">, he no selle; What he du? Masser got <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> enuf, wheat enuf, cyder enuf, ebery ting enuf; <HI>Jack</HI> he trash, he trash, dis bin full, dat bin full, ebery bin full, poor fok he no lette have, what he du, what poor fok du&punc; ah Masser! <HI>Jack</HI> pitty poor fok.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why you black Bastard, han't you victuals enough to stop your mouth?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JACK.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yesse, Sir, only pity poor fok cause he got no round dollar.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>DAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, what's that to you whether 'tis round or square so you live well? There's a hundred mechanics don't live half so well as you do.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JACK.</SPEAKER>
<P>I no dat, Masser.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="015290_0008_0F98CF304E425C30">
<SPEAKER>WIFE.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do wish our <HI>Jack</HI> wou'd mind his own business, and not be always a talk|ing of things that don't concern him at all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come Wife, bring on the goose, else I sha'n't have no room for't; I've been oblig'd to unbutton to let in the beef.&mdash; Come, who among you can remember the text?&mdash;Take care! don't grease my Sabbath-day coat, You.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JOTHAM.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can't remember the chap<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">r exactly, Father, but I think the words was <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">&punc; A <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ab of dove's dung was sold for&mdash; I f<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">rget&punc; for how much&mdash;but our Minister preach'd quite a good sermon, and stuck <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> down&punc; well to his text.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">.</SPEAKER>
<P>I thought he seem'd greatly <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> but my child was so tensome&punc; and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> such a noise, I coud'n't tell head nor <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">ll of the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">, only that he had one <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span">&punc;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARM<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">&punc;</SPEAKER>
<P><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> was that daughter <HI>Sarah?</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SARA<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">.</SPEAKER>
<P><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> this, pray Father, that <HI>He <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> people shall curse <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>DAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Does that mean so, Father? I think <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> heard Father say that <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> would not sell any if they were to live on <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> as the Irish <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">&punc;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why children&punc; children&punc; don't you know there's a spiritual meaning to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> which we have heard to day?
<STAGE>[<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span">]</STAGE>
He <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> hem!&mdash;why when <HI>Joseph</HI>'s <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> down into Egypt to buy <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span"> carried silver and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">
<PB N="9" REF="015290_0009_0F98CF3150B849E8">
hem!&mdash;and corn was sold for nothing else in scripture times. Hem!&mdash;now the true scrip|tural meaning is hum&mdash;why that if poor peo|ple come and bring me hard money&punc;&mdash;hem! and I refuse them, why then I'm to be curs'd, but if they have no ha<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">d money&mdash;hem!&mdash;I'm not oblig'd to let them have any. I chuse to go always by the true meaning of the bible, boys.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>DAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I think I have heard Father say, that a square dollar was as good as a round one, and I do really think it is, if we wou'd do what our <HI>Hartford</HI> paper tells us, I don't remember much on't tho'; but think he call'd it, A Looking Glass.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>A<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">! well I remember something of't to &mdash;why I'll tell ye, <HI>Dan</HI>; I have said that it was as good to pay rates with as any, but nothing more; I have got enough for that&mdash; why shou'd we be a spending our breath about that which will be of no service to us. Come let's dismiss the table.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WIFE.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay true enough You, I think it is very needless; do return thanks. Children be still.
<STAGE>[Here he proceeds, &amp;c.]</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, boys, I feel mightily re|fresh'd. Come <HI>Dan. Joth,</HI> come, go out to the barn along with me, and see the oxen I intend to st<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ll feed this year, better I be|lieve you never saw.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JOTHAM.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come so we will, Father. Come <HI>Dan.</HI></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Ex<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">nt&punc;</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>DAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Comes on then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="10" REF="015290_0010_0F98CF31C5942960">
<SPEAKER>MAT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, sister <HI>Sarah,</HI> now Father's gone I'll tell you what.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SARAH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well what?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Didn't you see our Lyon get hold of the goose's tail? Mother fetch'd him a good kick: Father roll'd his eyes, but c'u'dn't speak, because he was making a beginning. He! he! he!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SARAH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well I should laugh'd too if <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> had seen it. He! he! he! Be still! Fa|ther's coming.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, girls, how do you feel after dinner? Come make room! the boys and I have been out to see my oxen, better you never saw, <HI>Dan.</HI> Say, <HI>Joth.</HI> don't you think they'll fetch me five pounds a hundred next spring&punc;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>DAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Father, that they will, if the town folks don't rise and take them away, and I am bloody 'fraid they will; and if they should I doubt but the authority would justi|fy them in't.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why so, why so, <HI>Dan?</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>DAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Because the most of 'em an't able to buy at that price.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WIFE.</SPEAKER>
<P>That wou'd be a fine thing for them to come and take our things without liberty from us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>If they should I would flail 'em.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JOTHAM.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Father, I believe I must go.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Jack,</HI> fetch up the horse.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JACK.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yesse, Masser.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="11" REF="015290_0011_0F98CF3286440CB8">
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come boys, sit down; let's have one good song before you go, and part in peace, as we ought to do on Thanksgiving-Day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JOTHAM.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, that's done Father; do be|gin, and <HI>Dan.</HI> and I will sing chorus&mdash;what say <HI>Dan?</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>DAN.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Comes on then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JOTHAM.</SPEAKER>
<P>Father, be short, I want to go.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FARMER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, ay&mdash;mind the chorus. He, he, h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">m.</P>
<L>A Cabe of dove's dung on a time it was sold,</L>
<L>For nothing more short than silver and gold;</L>
<L>Silver and gold, silver and gold,</L>
<L>For nothing short of silver and gold.</L>
<L>No, but <HI>Jack</HI> wou'd persuade and make us think so,</L>
<L>That I am to blame and you my sons too,</L>
<L>You my sons too, you my sons too,</L>
<L>That I am to blame and you my sons too</L>
<L>But now to conclude and I bid you good night&punc;</L>
<L>I wish you well home, and so a good night:</L>
<L>So a good night, so a good night,</L>
<L>I wish you well home and then a good night.</L>
</SP>
<TRAILER>END OF THE COMEDY</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
